question: In this type of government, citizens collectively make decisions by voting directly on potential laws and policies. One of the earliest examples existed in ancient Athens.
A pioneer of Renaissance polyphony, this Flemish composer's works include predominantly sacred music like motets and masses. He's known for the complexity and expressiveness of his vocal pieces.

His dialogues explore themes of justice, the ideal society, and the nature of knowledge. A student of Socrates, his most famous student would go on to teach Alexander the Great. This thinker founded the Academy in Athens.
These chordates possess a notochord during development, along with gill slits and a hollow dorsal nerve cord. The group includes all mammals, birds, fish, and more.
These microscopic infectious agents have a simple structure and are capable of infecting all forms of life. To reproduce, they hijack the machinery of a host cell.
What company started a search engine project called "A9" to compete with Google and has a profitable cloud computing product while also being known for online shopping?
In Greek mythology, this hero known for his immense strength was given 12 almost impossible tasks to complete. He is also the inspiration for a 1997 Disney animated film.
In this Shakespeare play, a Scottish nobleman spurred by the prophecies of three witches murders his king to attain the throne. Plagued by guilt and fear, he becomes increasingly tyrannical.
Derived from a Greek word for 'love of wisdom,' this intellectual pursuit uses reason to explore ideas about existence, morality, knowledge, and values.

Often painted in bold color combinations, this Dutch Post-Impressionist had a troubled life yet went on to become one of the most celebrated artists posthumously. Some of his best-known works include 'Starry Night' and his self-portraits.

Found throughout the ocean, this phylum of marine invertebrates is characterized by radial symmetry, soft bodies, and tentacles armed with stinging cells.  Some form mutually beneficial relationships with clownfish.
Which NFL wide receiver who played 20 seasons, played his last game for the Seattle Seahawks, but won three superbowls with the San Francisco 49ers holds the NFL records for most total touchdowns?

This creature's riddle appears in Sophocles's play *Oedipus Rex*. She has the wings of an eagle, the body of a lion, and the head of a woman. In Greek myth, she devours those who fail to answer her question correctly.
This Italian explorer's voyages across the Atlantic helped pave the way for subsequent European colonialism in the Americas, though he did not reach the continental mainland.
This chemical element is highly reactive and the primary component of table salt. It has the symbol 'Na' and a silvery-white metallic appearance in its pure form.
This conflict pitted the Union and Confederacy against each other, dividing the nation as they battled over issues including states' rights and the enslavement of people.
In Greek religion, he was the god of war known for his violence and bloodshed. Identified with Mars in Roman mythology, he was an unpopular figure amongst many of the other gods of Olympus.

This fictional character, introduced in a novel published in 1937, was raised by his uncle after the tragic death of his parents. Known for his small stature and hairy feet, he embarks on an epic journey to destroy a powerful artifact that threatens the fate of his world.

This term often refers to the era from the fall of the Western Roman Empire to the Renaissance. Marked by feudalism and warfare, it's sometimes referred to as the 'Dark Ages,' though that label is debated.
Sharing a border with the Atacama Desert, the Pacific Ocean, and the Andes Mountains, this country features diverse terrain including a long coastline and the southernmost city in the world.

A Renaissance-era mathematician and astronomer from the Polish city of Thorn, this scholar challenged the long-held belief that the Earth was the center of the universe. His revolutionary work 'De revolutionibus orbium coelestium' proposed a heliocentric model, with the Sun at the center and the planets, including Earth, revolving around it. This theory, which contradicted the geocentric model of Ptolemy, laid the foundation for modern astronomy and is considered a key event in the Scientific Revolution.

Designed by French sculptor Frédéric Auguste Bartholdi, this towering neoclassical sculpture of a Roman goddess was originally made of copper sheets assembled on a framework of steel and concrete. It has a distinctive green patina color and was a gift from France to the United States. This iconic statue depicts a robed female figure holding a torch aloft and stands in New York Harbor.

A celebrated English novelist of the early 19th century, she is best known for her witty social satires that explored the societal norms and rigid class structures of Georgian-era Britain. Her most famous work, published anonymously in 1813, centers on the spirited Elizabeth Bennet and her confrontations with the haughty Mr. Darcy, ultimately leading to a romance that defies class prejudices.

Founded in 1867 as a small agricultural village in the Salt River Valley, this city was incorporated in 1881 and named after the mythical bird that cyclically regenerates from its own ashes. Known for its hot desert climate, it is now the largest state capital in the United States by population.

The only mammals capable of true, sustained flight, these nocturnal creatures possess an advanced biological sonar system that allows them to navigate and hunt in complete darkness. While most species feed on insects, some larger varieties consume fruits, nectar, or even the blood of other animals.

A vital transition metal found in trace amounts throughout the human body, it is the main component of hemoglobin, the protein in red blood cells responsible for transporting oxygen. With an atomic number of 26, this element's chemical symbol is derived from the Latin word 'ferrum,' meaning iron-bearing or iron-producing.

A Chinese philosopher who lived during the Warring States Period (475-221 BCE), he emphasized social harmony, respect for tradition, and the importance of a ruler's virtuous example in governing. His teachings, compiled in the Analects, formed the basis of the philosophical system known as Confucianism, which profoundly influenced East Asian societies.

The SI unit for electric current is named after this French physicist and mathematician, who formulated the fundamental relationship between electric current and magnetic fields in conductors. While not the primary inventor, he made significant contributions to the development of the telegraph. The unit represents the flow of one coulomb of charge per second.

Situated between Europe and Asia, this vast inland body of water has an area approximately the size of Japan and is often referred to as the world's largest lake, even though it has 'sea' in its name. With no outflows and a high salinity level, it is technically classified as a salt lake.

The last Roman emperor of the Julio-Claudian dynasty, this notorious ruler was infamous for his cruelty, extravagance, and rumored to have played the lyre while Rome burned during the Great Fire of 64 CE. He persecuted early Christians and faced multiple rebellions during his reign, which ended with his suicide in 68 CE.

Named after an Italian mathematician from Pisa, this numerical sequence, starting with 0 and 1, follows a simple pattern where each subsequent number is the sum of the two preceding ones (0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13...). This recursive sequence has been observed in nature, art, and even the architecture of spiral galaxies.

A prolific Austrian composer of the Classical era, this child prodigy began composing music at the age of five. He is renowned for his operas, such as 'The Marriage of Figaro,' 'Don Giovanni,' and 'Così fan tutte,' as well as his symphonies, concertos, and chamber works, which showcased his exceptional melodic and harmonic gifts.

This American novelist, known for her exploration of racial injustice and societal norms in the American South, gained widespread acclaim for her Pulitzer Prize-winning novel 'To Kill a Mockingbird.' Years later, she published 'Go Set a Watchman,' which was originally written as an early draft of her famous work.

Serving as the administrative capital of the European Union, this cosmopolitan city is home to the Grand Place, a stunning medieval square recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Known for its diverse architecture, cuisine, and vibrant cultural scene, it is also the headquarters of the European Commission and other EU institutions.

Built as a magnificent tomb for the Fourth Dynasty pharaoh Khufu, this iconic ancient Egyptian monument stands at a towering height of 481 feet and is the oldest and largest of the Seven Wonders of the Ancient World. Its massive scale and precise construction have baffled architects and historians for centuries.

This influential Greek philosopher, who lived in Athens during the 5th century BCE, is considered one of the founders of Western philosophy. He is renowned for his contributions to ethics, epistemology, and metaphysics, as well as his use of a question-and-answer approach to stimulate critical thinking and challenge assumptions.

One of the oldest and most widely practiced religions, this monotheistic faith traces its origins to the biblical figure of Abraham and emphasizes the importance of a covenant between God and the Jewish people. Its sacred texts, including the Torah and the Talmud, have shaped Jewish traditions, laws, and culture.

Located just below the Arctic Circle, this island nation is known for its stunning landscapes, including glaciers, volcanoes, and geothermic hot springs. Its capital city, Reykjavik, is the world's northernmost capital and is home to many cultural institutions that preserve the country's rich Norse heritage and mythological sagas.

Endothermic vertebrates that evolved from feathered theropod dinosaurs, these creatures are distinguished by their toothless beaks adapted for diverse diets and their ability to fly, though some members of this group have lost that capacity over time. Their warm-blooded nature and feathered bodies set them apart from reptiles.

Written in iambic pentameter, this tragic play by William Shakespeare tells the story of two star-crossed lovers from feuding families in Verona, Italy. Their forbidden love ultimately leads to their untimely deaths, cementing the play's reputation as one of the most famous and widely studied works in English literature.
Often found in deserts, these reptiles are equipped with scales, lay eggs, and regulate their body temperature by seeking sunlight or shade. Some species change color or have venomous bites.
Though short-lived as an entity, this alliance included major powers like Britain, France, and Russia and ultimately opposed the Central Powers during World War I.
The periodic table arranges them according to atomic number and groups them by shared properties. Some examples include carbon, iron, and gold.
This American writer depicted the hardships faced by migrant workers during the Great Depression in his novels "The Grapes of Wrath" and "Of Mice and Men.

With the world's longest coastline and most islands, this archipelago nation in Southeast Asia experiences tropical monsoons, earthquakes, and volcanic eruptions due to its position on the 'Ring of Fire'.
While this Italian Renaissance sculptor created several iconic pieces, perhaps his most famous is a 17-foot statue depicting a biblical hero famed for defeating a giant.
This celestial body, which appears red in the night sky due to iron oxide, has a thin atmosphere and is home to the largest volcano in the solar system, Olympus Mons.

A pioneer in the development of psychoanalysis, this Austrian neurologist proposed that the unconscious mind drives behaviors. His concepts such as the id, ego, and superego gained widespread influence.
He proposed the theory of special relativity, revolutionizing our understanding of space and time. His famous equation E=mc² reveals the relationship between energy and mass.
Found primarily in Africa, this is the largest living land animal and boasts a prehensile trunk used for drinking, grasping, and communication. The adults have large tusks made of ivory.

An archetypal Renaissance man, this Italian polymath conceptualized designs centuries ahead of their time, including plans for a helicopter and concentrated solar power. His genius spanned art, science, invention, and more, but he is most renowned for paintings like the Mona Lisa.

Flowing through Central and Western Europe, this major river has served as an important commercial transportation route for centuries. While its source is in the Swiss Alps, it travels over 800 miles and forms much of the border between France and Germany before emptying into the North Sea, with historic castles and vineyards dotting its scenic banks.

A member of the columbidae family, these predominantly white birds have been known for their ability to find their way home from great distance. These birds are symbolic of peace across many cultures and lend their name to a popular brand of soap.

This prolific 20th century Spanish artist spent much of his adult life in Paris. He experimented across mediums like sculpture and printmaking, and his early works featured somber figures and blue tones, while African masks influenced his later distinctive fragmented style. He is best known for renowned for co-founding the Cubist movement.

The heaviest US president at over 300 pounds, this leader emphasized economic influence over military might in foreign policy. After his presidency, he became the only person to also serve as Chief Justice of the Supreme Court, heading both executive and judicial branches. An oft-told anecdote involves him getting stuck in a White House bathtub.

One of the most influential composers of the 20th century, his neoclassical period saw a return to 18th century styles and forms. His early works exhibited classical structures before his iconoclastic ballets like 'The Rite of Spring' sparked a riot at their premiere in Paris.

Which beloved children's book character, who first appeared in a 1900 book by A.A. Milne, lives in the Hundred Acre Wood and has friends like Piglet, Tigger, and Eeyore? This honey-loving bear with a distinct yellow fur color has been featured in numerous films, television shows, and merchandise.

A landlocked country in South Asia, its territory contains ancient Buddhist monasteries and diverse wildlife. But it is best known for its dramatic Himalayan mountain landscapes, including the world's tallest peak, Mount Everest.
Based on an E.T.A. Hoffmann fairy tale, this beloved Christmas ballet composed by Tchaikovsky features characters like the Mouse King and Sugar Plum Fairy fending off the evil Mouse Queen.
A fundamental shape in Euclidean geometry, squares are a subset of these shapes. They feature four right angles and opposite sides that are parallel and equal in length.

This planet has over 80 known moons. Though smaller than Jupiter, it is still larger in diameter than any dwarf planet, with a mostly nitrogen atmosphere and methane lakes on its surface. It is the sixth planet from the sun and has a distinctive system of rings.

This is an epic poem from early English literature, though its setting is in Scandinavia. It is likely over 1000 years old and the one copy is in the Nowell Codex. It features alliterative verse and following a hero's battles against monstrous creatures.
A 19th century American poet who celebrated individuality and democracy in free verse, his groundbreaking major work titled after himself found both widespread critical acclaim and controversy.
Previously known as Edo, this Asian capital is the largest and most populous metropolitan area worldwide. It is home to the Imperial Palace, the official residence of the Emperor of Japan.
This classic Gothic novel, first published anonymously in 1818, is subtitled 'The Modern Prometheus' and narrated in part by a man sailing to explore the North Pole. It was written by Mary Shelley.
Derived from the Latin phrase 'media voce', this verb form indicates the subject acts upon itself, like in the example 'The door opened' where the door is not actively doing the opening.

Described as an intense period of heightened creativity and productivity, this psychological state is sometimes linked to mental illness, though not everyone who experiences it has an underlying disorder.

A founder of French Impressionist painting, he is renowned for his landscape scenes depicting the Japanese bridge in his garden at Giverny as well as his iconic water lily series experimenting with light and color.

One of the most famous Hollywood actresses of her era, she was renowned for her beauty, multiple marriages, and philanthropy. She became the first celebrity to be paid $1 million for a single film role.

A leading Post-Impressionist painter from the Netherlands, he was known for his distinctive style featuring swirling brushwork and bold colors, exemplified in his famous sunflower series. A renowned anecdote involves him severing his own ear.

Though primarily prose, this work from the Romantic era features interludes of poetry and tells a tale of doomed love and revenge. It's set against the bleak Yorkshire moors and features the characters of Heathcliff and Catherine. It was written by the sister of Charlotte Bronte, the author of Jane Eyre.

Which British rock band, formed in London in the 1960s, is known for their iconic album covers, progressive rock sound, and concept albums like 'The Wall' and 'The Dark Side of the Moon'? This band, whose founding members included Roger Waters, David Gilmour, and Nick Mason, has sold over 250 million records worldwide.

Which American author, who wrote the novel 'The Human Stain' and the short story 'Everyman,' won the Pulitzer Prize for Fiction in 1998 for his book about the life of a retired professor? His literary alter ego, Nathan Zuckerman, narrates several of his books.

Which renowned British artist, who pioneered the abstract art movement in the early 20th century, is known for his distinctive canvases featuring geometric shapes and bold colors? This artist, who co-founded the Vorticist movement, produced works like 'Composition with Red Blue and Yellow' and 'Black on Maroon.'

Which ancient Greek philosopher, who was a student of Socrates and a teacher of Aristotle, founded the Academy in Athens? This philosopher, who wrote dialogues such as 'The Republic' and 'Symposium,' is considered one of the most influential thinkers in Western philosophy.

An acclaimed Baroque composer whose early training focused on the harpsichord, he composed an extensive range of instrumental works in addition to his renowned choral pieces while residing in Leipzig, including the monumental 'St. Matthew Passion.'

This American inventor, who held over 1,000 patents, founded a prominent research laboratory in New Jersey. He is best known for developing the first practical incandescent light bulb and establishing the first electric power distribution system.

This Russian novelist and playwright, who lived from 1828 to 1910, is considered one of the greatest writers of all time. Some of his most famous works include 'Crime and Punishment,' 'The Brothers Karamazov,' and 'Notes from Underground.'

This French artist, who lived from 1834 to 1917, is renowned for his Impressionist paintings, which often depicted scenes of modern Parisian life. His most famous works include 'Luncheon on the Grass' and 'Olympia.'

This American author, who lived from 1919 to 1984, is best known for writing the classic novels 'The Catcher in the Rye' and 'Franny and Zooey.' He was a reclusive figure who avoided public attention for much of his life.

An American writer known for his macabre and mysterious stories, his haunting prose and explorations of themes like madness and guilt established him as a master of Gothic literature. Name this author who gained recognition with his poem 'The Raven'.

A German-born physicist, his groundbreaking work in the early 20th century transformed our understanding of space, time, and gravity. His theory of general relativity and the equation E=mc^2 are cornerstones of modern physics.

This Southeast Asian metropolis, home to the iconic Petronas Twin Towers, boasts a vibrant blend of cultures. Name of this city which is home to three of the ten largest shopping malls and is the capital of Malaysia.
A pivotal figure in the American Revolution, he served as commander-in-chief of the Continental Army. His image adorns the U.S. dollar bill. Name the first president of the United States.
A hero of Greek mythology, he was the son of Zeus and known for his exceptional strength. He completed twelve arduous labors, including slaying the Nemean lion and capturing the Cretan Bull.

This economic principle was first named by Scottish writer James Denham-Steuart in his 'Inquiry into the Principles of Political Economy'. Adam Smith also described this principle in his 1776 'Wealth of Nations'. This model of price determination explains the relationship between the availability of a product and its price.

Built for the 1889 World's Fair, this Parisian landmark is a wrought-iron structure offering panoramic city views. Its engineer, Gustave Eiffel, also designed the internal framework for the Statue of Liberty.
The largest flightless bird native to South America, it possesses a distinctive long neck and powerful legs. It can reach speeds of over 40 miles per hour, using its shaggy plumage to spot predators.
A Polish composer and pianist of the Romantic era, he is renowned for his expressive nocturnes and technically demanding études. His music showcased the emotional range of the piano.

The massive star at the center of our solar system, its nuclear reactions provide heat and light to Earth. Its surface temperature exceeds 10,000 degrees Fahrenheit, and its immense gravity holds the planets in orbit.

The oldest of the grand tours that make up men's professional tennis, this annual tournament has been held at the All England Club in London since 1877. Players are required to wear all-white clothing, and strawberries and cream are a beloved spectator tradition associated with this prestigious event.

A literary genre popularized in the early 19th century, it emphasizes the individual's expression of emotion and imagination, rejecting the rationality that had been prevalent. English poets like Wordsworth, Coleridge, and Byron were pioneers, producing works like 'Kubla Khan' and 'She Walks in Beauty.'

Associated with France and championed by figures like Voltaire and Diderot, this 18th century intellectual movement emphasized reason, individualism, and challenging traditional authority. Its ideals inspired revolutions in America and France, ultimately influencing modern democracy and human rights principles.

Derived from the Greek words for 'life' and 'light,' this natural phenomenon occurs when special marine algae are disturbed by waves, producing a striking glow. Locations ideal for witnessing this dazzling 'glowing beach' effect include Australia's Jervis Bay and Puerto Rico's Mosquito Bay.

These small nocturnal creatures emit high-pitched chirps despite being mammals. Their name derives from an ancient Greek term including 'blind,' as they were once thought to be sightless rodents. Name these mammals which use echolocation to navigate their surroundings.

A former Russian capital from 1712 to 1918, this planned city was founded by Peter the Great as Russia's 'window to Europe.' Located on the Neva River delta, it features numerous canals and Baroque architecture, lending it the moniker 'Venice of the North.' Its famed attractions include the Hermitage Museum.

This four-time Formula One World Champion from Britain shares his last name with a smash hit Broadway musical. He is one of the most successful drivers in the history of the sport. He holds records for most race wins, pole positions, and podium finishes. Often commended for his clean driving style, he was knighted in 2009.

Also known as the 'Crescent City,' this Southern U.S. city is renowned worldwide for its annual Mardi Gras festival and as the birthplace of jazz music. Its French Quarter district features iron-laced balconies and the famed Bourbon Street nightlife.

A titan of American literature, this novelist explored themes of morality and identity through thought-provoking allegories and complex protagonists. His most famous works include 'The Scarlet Letter,' a masterpiece delving into sin and guilt in Puritan New England.

A coveted recipient of ballet's highest honor, the Ordre des Arts et des Lettres, this Russian dancer pioneered a fluid, gravity-defying style and choreographed roles like Scheherazade and The Dying Swan. He founded her own touring company after defecting from the Soviet Union in 1961.

The tangent function gives these numbers when its input is in the 2nd or 4th quadrant. Using these numbers as exponents is defined in terms of a reciprocal. The absolute value function changes them. Defining their square roots requires imaginary numbers. Integers that are not natural numbers are either zero or one of these. Name these numbers that are less than zero.

This Britsh author wrote world's longest-running play, 'The Mousetrap' which has been performed in London since 1952. She wrote six novels under the psuedonym Mary Westmacott. She is best known for her murder-mystery novels revolving around fictional detectives Hercule Poirot and Miss Marple. Name this author of 'Murder on the Orient Express'.

This work includes a production of Don Juan Triumphant, a work written by the title character. The song "Think of Me" proves that one character can replace Carlotta as soprano; that character becomes engaged to Raoul, with whom he sings "All I Ask of You." "The Music of the Night" is sung by the title character of what Andrew Lloyd Webber musical about a deformed man who lives under an opera house?

The plan for this city was designed by the French architect Pierre L'Enfant. The Anacostia River flows across the eastern side of this city, whose Orange and Blue metro lines pass through Foggy Bottom. This city is encircled by a "Beltway" that crosses Montgomery County, Maryland and then enters Virginia. For your answer the Lincoln Memorial is found in what national capital on the Potomac River in the District of Columbia?

The three types of this material differ by their mineral and gas content; rhyolitic and andesitic types contain more silicon dioxide and are more viscous. The basaltic type is hottest, forms due to partial melting in the mantle, and flows fastest. Once any type reaches the planet's surface, it is known as lava. Name the molten rock which forms beneath volcanoes.

During one of these events, what is observed is based on the viewer's location relative to the path of totality. Viewers of them might see the annulus or corona, if they are standing in the antiumbra. Viewers standing in the penumbra will see a partial form, while during a total one, the corona may be seen. Name this event in which the moon appears to block out the sun.

The title figure looks "a little like a military man" in this group's song about a meter maid, "Lovely Rita." Peter Frampton starred in a movie based on this group's album Sergeant Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band. They recorded the album Abbey Road shortly before breaking up in 1970. Name this band from Liverpool, England whose hit "Eleanor Rigby" was written by Paul McCartney.

The Dewar equation defines this quantity for density-dependent variables. Species that exhibit exponential population growth appear to lack this value, and in logistic population growth, the per capita rate of increase approaches zero near this value. Name this ecological term, often denoted k, which is the maximum population that can be sustained by an ecosystem.

This shape is traced out by the set of all points that are equidistant from a focus and a directrix. It is the only conic section that can be graphed as a function. It is the shape of the height versus time graph of a ball tossed straight in the air. Identify this shape that is traced out by the graph of any quadratic function.

When James Madison revised this, it called for 7-year terms of office for Senators and 3-years terms for House members. Proposed by Edmund Randolph as 15 resolutions, more notable aspects of this plan included three branches of government and representation determined by population for both Houses. Identify this plan of government, named for the home state of Madison and Randolph, as well as Thomas Jefferson.

The fundamental theorem of arithmetic states that every positive integer can be uniquely represented as a product of these numbers. Special types of these numbers are named after Fermat and Mersenne. To find these numbers, one may use the Sieve of Eratosthenes, in which one crosses off all multiples of two, then all multiples of three, and so on. For your answer give these numbers whose only factors are one and themselves.

Other than James and John, this is the only man to witness the Transfiguration of Jesus. He cut off the guard Malchus's ear during a showdown in the Garden of Gethsemane. His symbol is a pair of crossed keys, and this man is said to have been crucified upside down. Name this apostle of Jesus and brother of Andrew, who denied Jesus three times and was the first pope.

One mission in this program docked with the spacecraft used by Soyuz 19. The numerically first mission in this program was retroactively named after a fire burst out during a test run. Harrison Schmitt, a geologist, was part of its last mission, number 17. One mission in this program spawned the line, "Houston, we've had a problem." Name this NASA program whose mission 11 saw man first walk on the moon.

In one scene, this character causes a cat to run chaotically through the house by giving it "pain-killer." He plays Robin Hood with Joe Harper. He gets trapped in McDougal's Cave with Becky Thatcher, where he sees Injun Joe hiding. Earlier, he had persuaded his friends to whitewash a fence for him. Name this companion of Huck Finn in several novels by Mark Twain.

In 1969, this man seized power in a bloodless coup by overthrowing King Idris. This author of 'The Green Book' handed over the Lockerbie bombers after being visited by Nelson Mandela. After protests against this man's rule began, a rebel government was established in the city of Benghazi. In the town of Sirte, this man was killed alongside his son Mutassim in 2011. Name this former leader of Libya.

This man was targeted in the Conway Cabal, which was partially due to his losses at Germantown and Brandywine. He declared political parties to be a "frightful despotism" and warned against engaging in "entangling alliances" in his Farewell Address, after which his former Vice President John Adams became President. Name this leader of the Continental Army who became the first President of the United States.

This planet's 700 kilometer-wide impact crater Rembrandt was discovered by the MESSENGER spacecraft orbiting it. Like the Moon, part of its surface is known as Weird Terrain; that part is opposite its largest crater, the Caloris Basin. It is the smallest planet in our solar system, and this planet and Venus are the only two without moons. Name this planet whose year is only 88 days long, the innermost planet.

A cleaning technique often used on jewelry uses this type of wave to produce bubbles. This type of sound wave has a frequency of 20 kilohertz or higher, just above the range of human hearing. Name this frequency range used by bats for echolocation, and by humans to check the health of unborn babies.

At the end of this story, the title object is revealed to be worth at most five hundred francs. Monsieur Loisel frantically searched for the title object after a ball, but to no avail. After Mathilde loses it, she and her husband take odd jobs to pay off the loans taken out to pay for a replacement. Name this Guy de Maupassant short story about a piece of jewelry.

This is the only element for which Schrodinger's equation can be solved exactly. Isotopes of this element include tritium and deuterium. Its diatomic form is released when sodium reacts with water. It is the only nonmetal in Period 1 of the periodic table. Name this lightest element, which has a chemical symbol of H.

This dynasty inherited portions of the Netherlands after the death of the Burgundian monarch Charles the Bold at the Battle of Nancy. One ruler of this family won the Battle of Pavia and captured Francis I of France in the process; that ruler was Charles V. Another ruler from this family lost Silesia to Fredrick the Great; that ruler was Maria Theresa. Identify this dynasty with Austrian and Spanish branches.

This character was named after the wife of King Leontes in The Winter's Tale. This character forms an organization called S.P.E.W., and purchases a half-cat, half-kneazle known as Crookshanks. Though she is called a "mudblood" because of her dentist parents, she is smart enough to have memorized "Hogwarts: A History." Name this female companion to Harry and Ron in the "Harry Potter" series.

This instrument plays the opening Promenade in Mussorgsky's Pictures at an Exhibition, as well as the rising theme C-G-C in the opening of Richard Strauss' Thus Spake Zarathustra. This instrument's tone can be lowered by one-and-a-half steps by pressing either its third or both its first and second valves. Name this brass instrument whose timbre is slightly brighter than that of a cornet.

This city was founded by Cadmus after following a cow until it sat. This city was besieged by the Sphinx, as all travelers who entered it were forced to either solve its riddle or be eaten. To avenge the sleight done to him by Eteocles, Polyneices led a group of seven warriors against this city. Identify this Greek city, the home of Antigone and Oedipus.

This character interrupts a round of storytelling by attacking a stash of wine-skins. He wears a washbasin as a helmet while calling himself the Knight of the Sorry Face. He owns the horse Rocinante and frequently speaks of his love for Dulcinea to his friend Sancho Panza. Name this self-proclaimed knight from La Mancha who fights against windmills in a book by Miguel de Cervantes.

During this war, Andrew Jackson defeated the Creek at the Battle of Horseshoe Bend. Tecumseh died during the Battle of the Thames in this war. The White House was burned by the British Army during this war. Francis Scott Key composed the "Star Spangled Banner" during this conflict. Impressment of U.S. sailors was a major cause of this war. What 19th-century war between the U.S. and Britain was named for the year it began?

This man's secretary, Orville Babcock, and vice president, Schuyler Colfax, were accused in the scandals of the Whiskey Ring and Credit Mobilier. He captured Fort Donelson and opened the Mississippi River at Vicksburg before he was promoted to command all the Union armies and accepted the surrender of Robert E. Lee at Appomattox. Name this Union general and eighteenth President.

This revolutionary smartphone popularized touchscreens and mobile apps. Its release in 2007 transformed the way we communicate and access information. Name this now flagship product of Apple which sold over 230 million units in 2023.

Areas in this region with substantially reduced object distribution are known as Kirkwood gaps and are formed by the gravitational strength of the planet behind it. One body in this region has a satellite known as Dactyl. Besides Ida, other objects located here include Pallas, Vesta, and the smallest dwarf planet in the Solar System, Ceres. Name this ring of small astronomical bodies located between Mars and Jupiter.

In order to destroy the Hogyoku and defeat Aizen, this show's main character unleashes the final Getsuga Tensho. This anime's protagonist attains a new form while fighting against the Espada Ulquiorra. This anime begins when Rukia Kuchiki gives up her powers to the protagonist. Identify this anime featuring Ichigo Kurosaki where Soul Reapers battle Hollows.

In one story from this collection, Palamon and Arcite fight over the hand of Emelye, while in another story, an old hag notes that what women want most is to be in charge of their husbands. Those stories are told by, respectively, the Knight and the Wife of Bath, two of a group of pilgrims journeying to the shrine of Thomas à Becket in the title town. Name this collection of tales by Geoffrey Chaucer.

In this work, Unferth boasts about beating the protagonist in a swimming contest. As his dying action, the protagonist gives Wiglaf a royal gold collar. Partly taking place in the mead hall Heorot, this work presents Hrothgar, the king of the Danes, as helpless in battling a monster who comes nightly to eat warriors. Name this Old English epic poem in which the title hero kills Grendel and Grendel's mother.

This geographical feature has its lowest point at Bentley Trench. A lake here lies under Vostok Station. Mt. Erebus is found on Ross Island off itscoast, between Marie Byrd and Victoria lands. The Sentinel Range of the Ellsworth Mountains contains its highest peak, Vinson Massif, located on the Ronne Ice Shelf. Getting only 5-10 inches of precipitation a year, it is considered a desert. Identify this southernmost continent that contains the icy South Pole.

Channels that carry ions made of this element are blocked by some hypertension medications. Ions of this element and magnesium are concentrated in hard water, while its sulfate forms gypsum. Antacids use its carbonate, which forms limestone. Name this element found in dairy products that is used by the body to form teeth and bone structures, represented by the symbol Ca.

This man patented a smokeless propellant known as ballistite. Another of his inventions consisted of diatomaceous earth. He developed a substance containing nitrocellulose, saltpeter, wood pulp, and an explosive. Used in blasting gelatin, that explosive was also used in an earlier invention. Dynamite was created by what scientist whose namesake prizes are given out by the Swedish Academy of Sciences?

This structure was the site of the climactic scene in North by Northwest. A similar structure in Georgia was halted before Stone Mountain was completed. This sculpture designed by Gutzon Borglum is in the Black Hills. Name this large sculpture that contains the granite faces of four presidents.

For boasting of an affair with this goddess, Anchises was struck lame by Zeus. She and Persephone were forced to each spend a third of the year with Adonis. This goddess arrived on the island of Cythera after being born from sea foam, and she was trapped under a golden net with her lover Ares while she was married to Hephaestus. Name this Greek goddess of love and beauty.

The main characters of this book are allowed passage into Fort William Henry after Duncan Heyward tricks a sentinel by speaking French. This book's hero tries to rescue the two "females,"Alice and Cora Munro, after they are kidnapped by Magua. Name this novel set during the French and Indian War in which Natty Bumppo befriends Chingachgook and Uncas, and written by James Fenimore Cooper.

This man was the first to institute retirement and disability benefits. This man instituted the May Laws as part of his anti-Catholic program, kulturkampf. He manipulated the Schleswig- Holstein question into war with Austria and doctored the Ems Telegram to instigate an 1870 war with France. Name this "Iron Chancellor" of Prussia and Germany from 1862 to 1890.

The Aufbau principle explains how these particles are placed in their "shells." The discovery of these particles in cathode rays by J.J. Thomson led him to formulate the plum pudding model. The charge on one of these particles is also known as the fundamental charge. In the Bohr model of the atom, these particles orbit the nucleus. Name these negatively charged particles.

The difference quotient calculates this value for a secant, and the derivative is this for a tangent line. The product of these quantities for perpendicular lines is negative one. This is undefined for vertical lines, and for horizontal lines it is zero. It can be calculated as delta y over delta x. Name this quantity which is represented by m in the equation y = mx + b and measures the steepness of a line.

This woman allied with Walter White to push the failed Costigan-Wagner anti-lynching bill, but the President refused to publicly endorse it. She and Wendell Wilkie were the first honorary chairpersons of Freedom House. She arranged Marian Anderson's concert at the Lincoln Memorial. As a delegate to the UN from 1945-1952, she also helped draft the Declaration of Human Rights. Name this First Lady, the wife of Franklin D. Roosevelt.

Prince Calaf sings "Nessun dorma" in this composer's unfinished final work. Another opera by this composer sees Lieutenant Pinkerton marry the title character, Cio-Cio San (CHO CHO sahn), before returning to America. This composer of the unfinished Turandot also composed an opera about the poet Rodolfo's love for the seamstress Mimi, who dies of tuberculosis. Name this Italian who created Madame Butterfly and La Boheme.
answers: Giacomo Antonio Domenico Michele Secondo Maria Puccini

question: Characters in this novel include the Zoroastrian Fedallah, a Native American called Tashtego, and a South Sea islander named Queequeg. This novel's narrator begins by telling the reader to "call me Ishmael" and ends up clinging to a coffin when the captain of the Pequod and all but one of his crew are drowned. For your answer Herman Melville wrote what novel about Ahab's quest for the white whale?

Vast amounts of data concerning this body were gathered by the Clementine mission. Rilles are faults found on the surface of this body. The Tycho Crater and Montes Pyrenaeus are found here. Its movement is calculated using sidereal and synodic periods. This body's surface contains several maria, including the Sea of Tranquility. Name this celestial body that revolves around Earth.

This man came to power through the coup of 18 Brumaire. His forces defeated the Prussians at Jena and the combined Russian and Austrian forces at Austerlitz. His invasion of Russia was a failure because of the harsh winter. He spent the last years of his life exiled on St. Helena, and he sold the Louisiana Territory to America. Name this French emperor from Corsica who ruled after the French revolution

One novel by this man sees a recurring protagonist help to rescue his friend Chingachgook's betrothed Wah-ta!-wah from the Hurons. This man wrote another novel in which the angry Magua tries to kill Cora Munro, and the title person is not the protagonist Hawkeye, but rather Uncas. For ten points, name this author whose Leatherstocking Tales include The Deerslayer and The Last of the Mohicans.

This composer wrote a Clarinet Concerto in A Major for Anton Stadler, and he also composed a flute and harp concerto. He composed twelve variations on a French song with identical melody to "Twinkle Twinkle Little Star." He failed to complete his Requiem. His forty-first and last symphony is nicknamed Jupiter. Name this composer of Eine Kleine Nachtmusik and operas such as The Magic Flute

Cushion plants are found in the alpine form of this biome, which is also home to marmots, pikas, and chinchillas. The point at which this biome meets taiga is known as the treeline. Flora in this biome consists of lichens and mosses. Non-alpine forms of it have little vegetation due to permafrost. Name this biome that lacks tree growth, which can be found in Alaska and is home to caribou and reindeer.

This state contains the Tongass National Forest and the "Valley of Ten Thousand Smokes." The Alexander Archipelago is on one side of its "Inside Passage;" on the other side is this state's panhandle. The Brooks Range is an extension of the Rocky Mountains into this state. This state's city of Wasilla is a suburb of its largest city, Anchorage. Name this largest and northernmost U.S. state.

This man wrote that "injustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere" in his Letter from Birmingham Jail. This organizer of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference hoped that his children would be judged by "the content of their character" in his 1963 speech at the Lincoln Memorial. For your answer the "I Have A Dream" speech was given by what civil rights leader commemorated on a January holiday?

This city was named after the Pottawatomie for either "smelly onion place" or "skunk." An early road in this city crossed the "Nine-Mile Swamp" and Des Plaines (day PLAINS) River. Its Statistical Metropolitan Area includes Kenosha and Gary. This seat of Cook County is on the southwestern shore of Lake Michigan. Name this third largest city in the United States known as the "Windy City."

This non-Italian artist included a bare-chested torso in the background of his The Sacrament of the Last Supper. He included many cubes in the "disintegration" of his best-known painting, and also created a Lobster Telephone. His best-known painting includes several ants on a timepiece, as well as clocks which have the appearance of melting. Name this Spanish surrealist who painted The Persistence of Memory.

This artist's paintings of the New York City skyline include The Radiator Building, Night. White objects dot a blue painting by this artist in Sky Above Clouds. After her husband's death, she moved to a site where she painted Black Iris and another work bisected by a black stripe, Cow's Skull: Red, White, and Blue. Name this wife of Alfred Stieglitz, an American painter of flowers and the southwest.

In one episode in this work, the narrator tries to convince adults that he is drawing a snake digesting an elephant, which they confuse with a hat. The title character of this novella lived on an asteroid the size of a house before catching a rose in a lie and becoming lonely. Its title character visits seven planets, the last of which is Earth. Name this novel by Antoine de Saint-Exupéry.

Lee Deforest is considered one of the inventors of this technique in the early 1900s when he was working on space telegraphy. This form of radio communication involves the transmission of sinusoidal waves that have varying strength over time. Most early commercial radios used this technique due to its simplicity. Name this radio transmission methodology contrasted with frequency modulation.

In this novel, Charlotte Lucas marries William Collins. At the end of this novel, Lydia ends up marrying the villainous Mr. Wickham and Jane ends up marrying the very rich Mr. Bingley. Also at the end of this novel, a second marriage proposal by Fitzwilliam Darcy is finally accepted by Elizabeth Bennett. Name this Jane Austen novel in which Darcy and Elizabeth embody the two titular vices.

One creation story from this religion claims that all beings were sprung from one-fourth of Purusa, while the Puranas describe how the world is created, sustained, and destroyed by three gods in the form of a lotus flower. Other texts important in this religion include the Mahabharata, the Ramayana, and the Vedas (VAYduhs). What religion centers on the three gods Vishnu, Shiva, and Brahma?

The sun deity of this myth system hid in a cave after her brother threw a flayed horse at her, but she was lured out with a dance and a mirror. After visiting the underworld, one of this myth system's gods washed his face, giving birth to the storm god Susano'o, the moon god Tsukuyomi, and the sun goddess Amaterasu. Kami are the spiritual essences of what mythological system practiced in Japan?

This office is symbolized by gold and silver keys. The time during which this office is vacant is termed sede vacante. The holder of this office is elected in a conclave of the College of Cardinals and wears the Ring of the Fisherman, which depicts St. Peter, the first holder of this office. Identify this head of the Roman Catholic Church, whose current holder is from Argentina.
answers: Successor of the Prince of the Apostles
Supreme Pontiff of the Universal Church
Archbishop and Metropolitan of the Roman Province
Sovereign of the State of Vatican City
Servant of the Servants of God

question: This work includes the aria "Un bel di," describing a beautiful day when a ship will arrive with the singer's husband after three years away. Unfortunately, the consul Sharpless informs the title character that her husband has married Kate, an American worman. Lieutenant Pinkerton abandons the title character of what Giacomo Puccini opera about Cio-Cio San, a Japanese woman known by an insect nickname?

In publishing, this six-letter term describes a set of journal issues published in the same year. It also describes the sound level output from a computer or television. Density equals mass divided by a quantity with this name. For your answer give this term for the amount of space an object occupies, which for a cube equals side length cubed.

The four quarters of this person's residence were each dedicated to a different god. This ruler's forces were nearly done in by enemy chariots when crossing the Orontes at the Battle of Kadesh. This son of Seti I built several complexes, including a tomb in the Valley of the Queens for his wife Nefertari. Name this nineteenth dynasty Egyptian pharaoh, known as "Ozymandias" in Greek.

4 times the infinite sum one, minus one third, plus one fifth, minus one seventh, et cetera, equals this number. It is approximately equal to 355/113, 333/106, and 22/7. One hundred eighty degrees equals this many radians, and this number is the area of a circle with radius 1. For your answer the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter equals what number, about 3.14?

The distribution of these items was outlawed in Mumbai, India after a 2005 flood was partly blamed on blocked drains throughout the city. In 2011, Italy was the first European nation to completely ban their distribution, though biodegradable ones are still legal. Identify these items banned in Seattle as of July 2012, though consumers will still be able to purchase paper ones, or use their own cloth ones.

One copy of this document was sent to the Cinque ports. It notably banned the use of fish-weir traps, and Innocent III tried to make it void after one of its signers repented to him. This agreement created a council of 25 barons, who fought a war after the loser of the Battle of Bouvines failed to follow it. Name this document which established habeas corpus, a charter signed at Runnymede by John of England.

J.M.W. Turner painted one of these things before it was to be "broken up" in his The Fighting Temeraire. A black man stands in a small brown one of these things in a Winslow Homer painting. A John Copley painting showing many of these includes a group of people on one of them as Brook Watson is being rescued from a shark attack. Name these sea vessels which are often shown in naval war scenes.

Mack, Dora, and Lee Chong try to throw a party for Doc in this author's novel Cannery Row. This author wrote about Kino's encounter with the title object in The Pearl. Two migrant workers, George and Lennie, are the main characters in his Of Mice and Men; another work features the Joad family and other "Okies." Name this American author of The Grapes of Wrath.

This planet's equator is home to an elevated region known as the Tharsis Bulge, which is located near the Valles Marineris. It was visited by the Viking probes and is home to the highest mountain in the Solar System, the extinct volcano Olympus Mons. This planet is orbited by two small moons named Deimos and Phobos. For your answer a network of naturally occurring "canals" is on what planet between Earth and Jupiter?

The Neptunbrunnen is a fountain in this city, and its Museum Island is a World Heritage Site. The Charlottenburg Palace can be found in it, and Karl-Marx-Allee is a major boulevard. The Reichstag and the Brandenburg Gate are landmarks in this city that was divided by a wall until 1989. Name this capital of Germany.

This term originated from shapes that had non-integer dimensions. One of them is composed of repeating cardioids and circles. Other examples include the Sierpinski Triangle, which consists of repeating equilateral triangles within a larger triangle, and the Koch snowflake, which has an infinite perimeter but a finite area. Name these self-similar mathematical constructs that include the Mandelbrot one.

A revolution in this country was led by the Katipunan and was sparked by the execution of Jose Rizal. One of its presidents, Ferdinand Marcos, was blamed for the assassination of Benigno Aquino, whose widow Corazon became president. Name this island nation, the site of the World War II Battle of Leyte Gulf and the Spanish-American War Battle of Manila Bay.

When this athlete was the 2004 NBA Rookie of the Year, he became the youngest person ever to win that award. This player was criticized for 3-for-14 shooting in a Game 5 loss to the Boston Celtics in the 2010 playoffs and the owner of his former team, Dan Gilbert, published a letter after this player left in free agency. Name this former Cleveland Cavalier who televised his decision to accept a contract with the Miami Heat.

According to the Koran, all angels, except Satan, prostrated themselves before this figure due to his knowledge. He was cursed to "eat bread until he returned to the ground." In the New Testament, he is seen as the source of death for all men. His transgression is revealed to God when he is seen wearing a fig leaf. His rib was used to make his wife, Eve. Name this Biblical figure, the first man.

In one poem, this writer depicted the blacksmith named Basil as the father of Gabriel, who is the sweetheart of the title daughter of Benedict. In another poem, this writer depicted the evil magician named Pearl-Feather who is defeated by a title Native American. Name this American writer who wrote Evangeline and The Song of Hiawatha.

This city contains the neo-gothic Votive Church, and its Karlskirche is the largest Baroque Cathedral north of the Alps. It is the capital of a country with such states as Burgenland, Tyrol, and Styria. This city's Ring Boulevard was ordered to be restructured by Franz Joseph I, and it lies on the Danube just upriver from Bratislava, the capital of Slovakia. Name this capital of Austria.

The European cuckoo is a brood example of this type of bird, and mistletoe is a common plant of this type. Trypanosomes, which cause sleeping sickness, are one of many protist species of this type, and the blood fluke is this kind of worm that uses a snail as an intermediate host. Name these organisms, like ticks and tapeworms, that feed in or on the body of another organism, harming it in the process.

Near the end of this novel, Marya Bolkonskaya marries a cavalry officer named Nikolay. Nikolay's sister later marries the former husband of the most fascinating woman in Petersburg, Helene Kuragina. By the end of this novel, Natasha Rostova marries Pierre Bezukhov. Name this Leo Tolstoy novel that is notoriously long.

One deity from this myth system received the four winds as a gift from his grandfather and used them to kill its creator goddess, Tiamat. Another deity from this myth system corresponds to the Sumerian Inanna and removed seven objects of clothing at seven different gates in the underworld. For your answer Marduk and Ishtar appear in what myth system that also includes the legendary king Gilgamesh?

This piece follows the tenor Air "Thou shalt break them" and, after a break, precedes "I know that my Redeemer liveth." King George II supposedly stood during its 1743 London premiere. It includes the line "King of Kings and Lord of Lords," and notes "He shall reign forever and ever." Name this choral excerpt from Handel's oratorio Messiah, named for its opening word of praise.

In this work, potted plants are visible above the left shoulder of one of the central figures, and part of a red barn can be seen on the right. Architecture in the background is in the Carpenter form of its title style. This painting's models were the painter's dentist and his sister, Nan. Name this regionalist Grant Wood work that depicts a woman and her pitchfork-holding father.

In one novel, this writer depicted Catherine as the lover of Frederic Henry. In another novel, this writer depicted Maria as the lover of Robert Jordan. In a third novel by this writer, Frances is replaced by Lady Brett Ashley as the mistress of Robert Cohn ("CONE"). Name this American writer who wrote A Farewell to Arms, For Whom the Bell Tolls, and The Sun Also Rises.

In the movie Cats & Dogs, he provided the voice for Lou the Beagle. In another movie, he and his sister, played by Reese Witherspoon, are transported to the 1950s sitcom Pleasantville. He played a Depression-era jockey who somehow finds success on an undersized horse in Seabiscuit. Name this actor who starred as Peter Parker in the first trilogy of Spider-Man movies.

Neoptolemus killed King Priam in the final stages of this event, after which Aeneas fled with his son. This event began after the Judgement of Paris and Helen's abduction from King Menelaus of Sparta. After nine years, it finally ended after Greek soldiers got past enemy gates while hiding in a giant wooden horse. Name this conflict in Greek mythology that featured warriors like Hector and Achilles.

After initiation into the Khalsa in this religion, adherents must wear a wooden comb, known as the "kanga", and a steel bracelet, known as the "kara", which are two of the five K's. Arjun Dev compiled this religion's holy text, the Adi Granth, which contains many of the sayings of the first leader, or guru, of this religion. Identify this religion founded by Nanak, whose adherents are mostly found in the Punjab region.

In this work, a floating female carries a flame lit lamp and a soldier is clutching a broken sword from where a flower is growing. This work also has a distraught horse in the background and a bull standing over a woman, who is grieving over a dead child. Name this work by Pablo Picasso created to bring world notice to the bombings during the Spanish Civil War.

Two poems originally written in this language begin "Willow of crystal, a poplar of water" and "Tonight I can write the saddest lines;" the latter poem ends a collection that also includes twenty love poems. In a novel written in this language, the town of Macondo is founded by Jose Buendia. "Sunstone" and One Hundred Years of Solitude were written in what language, used by Octavio Paz, Pablo Neruda, and Gabriel Garcia Marquez?

The second king of this country, who started the International African Association and worked with Henry Stanley to establish a colony called the Congo Free State, was Leopold II. During World War I, several battles were fought near its town of Ypres, which is in its Flanders region. This country gained its independence in 1830 from the Netherlands. For your answer Walloons and Flemings live in what country whose capital is Brussels?

One member of this band narrowly survived a plane crash along with DJ AM. In one song they sang "say it ain't so, I will not go, turn the lights off, carry me home" and in another they sang about how "your smile fades in the summer." Name this punk band, who in addition to "All the Small Things" and "Feeling This" recorded "Stay Together for the Kids" and "I Miss You."

This person was described as a "beloved physician" by a "coworker," and this man's feast day is October 18. He dedicated two books to Theophilus, including one that begins with the Ascension and describes the missionary journeys of that "coworker," Paul. Name this author of Acts of the Apostles and the third Gospel of the New Testament.

Amendments affecting this branch of government include the Twelfth and Twenty-second. One member of this entity is granted the "power to grant reprieves and pardons." The most recent addition to this entity is the Department of Homeland Security. It was set up by Article II of the Constitution. What is this branch of government responsible for enforcing the laws and headed by the President?

This is the major key in which both Sergei Prokofiev's "Classical" Symphony and J.S. Bach's Air on a G String were written. A basic guitar chord of this type does not play the fifth and sixth strings and leaves open the fourth string as the root of the chord. Johann Pachelbel wrote a canon in this key whose relative minor is B minor. Name this major key whose key signature has two sharps.

One figure involved in this event is drunk with the blood of saints. During it, seven vials are poured by seven angels in order to wreak havoc. It is set to take place on the Hill of Megiddo. Death, Famine, War, and Pestilence are the "Four Horsemen" of this event. Identify this Biblical event where the forces of good and evil will do battle one last time.

The first Supreme Court case to deal with this doctrine was Regents of the University of California v. Bakke, which dealt with the question of whether it should be viewed as reverse discrimination. Although it also covers jobs and promotions what doctrine is most controversial for its attempts to provide members of disadvantaged groups enhanced opportunities for admission to educational institutions?

Parts of this continent named for 19th century sailors include Palmer Land and Wilkes Land. Vostok is a Russian station on this continent, parts of which are claimed by Norway, Argentina, and New Zealand. British naval officer Robert Scott died on this continent, which was more successfully explored by Roald Amundsen using sled dogs. Name this coldest continent, the site of penguin colonies and the South Pole.

Most stories hold that this deity, not Athena, blinded the prophet Tiresias. She cursed the nymph Echo to repeat only what others had said. This figure gave birth to Hephaestus and later threw him out of Olympus because of his ugliness. After her husband impregnated Leto, she refused to let Leto give birth on land. Name this Greek goddess and wife of Zeus.
Three of these creatures named Brontes, Steropes, and Arges. Name this race of one-eyed giants from Greek mythology.

This state of matter is the initial and final phase in regelation, and it is to the left of the triple point on phase diagrams. This starting point for sublimation is the most common state for elements at room temperature and pressure. One type of it is amorphous, though it generally is characterized by an orderly pattern on molecules. Name this state that includes crystals, the endpoint of freezing.

Some of the most important teachings of this religion include the Four Noble Truths and the Middle Way. One of the main branches of this religion is also known as the "School of Elders," while another is known as the "Great Vehicle." Those are the Theravada and Mahayana branches of this religion. Siddhartha Gautama founded what religion that also comes in Zen and Tibetan forms?

Paul Wittgenstein commissioned concertos for this instrument that used only the left hand. This instrument is said to have been invented by Bartolomeo Cristofori. It was originally named for its ability to play both loud and soft sounds, which made it an improvement over the clavichord and harpsichord. Name this musical instrument that has thirty-six black and fifty-two white keys.

He defended a campaign fund with his "Checkers Speech," which helped him maintain his role as Dwight Eisenhower's running mate. He was defeated in the 1962 race for Governor of California two years after losing a hotly contested election to John F. Kennedy. Name this 37th President of the United States, who resigned following the Watergate scandal.

While president of the Estates-General, this man presented the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen to Louis XVI. He refused to become dictator after the 1830 July Revolution. Earlier, he had helped to secure French aid to the American Revolution. Name this "Hero of Two Worlds," a French general who was George Washington's aide-de-camp.
answers: Marie-Joseph Paul Yves Roch Gilbert du Motier, Marquis de Lafayette

question: This building was constructed with help from Hiram, King of Tyre and Boaz. It was ostensibly built on Mount Moriah, which is now home to the Dome of the Rock. This building housed the Ark of the Covenant. After it was destroyed by Nebuchadnezzar, it was rebuilt, only to be destroyed again in 70 CE. Identify this place of worship first built by Solomon.

Cherenkov radiation exists when this value is exceeded. The ratio of this quantity in a vacuum to this quantity in a material is that material's index of refraction. It is squared and multiplied by mass to give energy in an equation derived by Einstein, E equals m c squared. Name this theoretical upper limit for the speed of any object, equal to about three hundred million meters per second.

At one point in this book, two characters recite nursery rhymes and the Gettysburg Address to avoid being hypnotized by a man with red eyes. The main character of this book meets several tentacled creatures, including one called Aunt Beast, while rescuing her father from Camazotz. Its title concept is a tesseract through which Meg Murry visits the fifth dimension. Name this novel by Madeleine L'Engle.

When air resistance exactly counteracts this force, an object has reached terminal velocity. The escape velocity is the minimum speed needed to overcome the effects of this force. On Earth, this force acts to accelerate a body at nine point eight meters per second squared. Name this force responsible for keeping objects on the ground.

These people recorded their rulers' accomplishments on tetun using the only complete written language of the pre-Columbian Americas. Leaders of these people include Pakal the Great and Hunac Ceel and their myths are collected in the Popol Vuh. Identify this Mesoamerican civilization that created the Long Count calendar and had cities at Tikal and Chichen Itza.

This object was delivered not with an inflatable "airbag" system like its predecessors, but with a "sky crane" system that was untested prior to its deployment, which was called "Seven Minutes of Terror." Its arrival at Gale Crater on August 6, 2012 was observed by the Odyssey orbiter. Name this semi-autonomous, car-sized rover that has been conducting experiments on a Mars for over 10 years.

Lewis defined these substances as acceptors of electron pairs. The presence of the hydronium ion is necessary in the Arrhenius definition. Strong examples of these substances include nitric and sulfuric, which fit the Bronsted-Lowry model as donors of hydrogen ions and turn blue litmus paper red. Name these substances with pH lower than 7 that neutralize bases.

During the Civil War, this city was defended by Fort St. Philip and controversially occupied by Union general Benjamin Butler. The Sieur de Bienville led a group of French settlers here in 1718. This city's suburb of Metairie contains the southern end of the Lake Pontchartrain Causeway. Its Lower Ninth Ward was damaged when levees were weakened by a 2005 storm. What Louisiana city was devastated by Hurricane Katrina?

This figure met his demise when he was struck by a piece of wood from his own vessel. While in Colchis visiting King Aeetes, he accomplished such tasks as yoking fire-breathing oxen and dispatching a group of warriors that sprang forth after dragon teeth were sown into the ground, all to get the Golden Fleece. He was aided in these tasks by his future wife Medea. Name this leader of the Argonauts.

This process's namesake constant is used in Fick's Law and an explanation of Brownian motion. This process is used during respiration to get oxygen into blood, and it then replaces that oxygen with carbon dioxide. It is synonymous with heat conduction, and this process in water is called osmosis. Name this process in which the random motion of particles causes them to spread to areas of lower concentration.

This owner of a stuffed elephant named Ella Funt plays a black-nosed sheep in a Christmas play and dresses up as "the baddest witch in the world." She has a cat named Picky-Picky until it dies, and she also sees herself in an infinite mirror. This best friend of Howie Kemp lives on the same street as Henry Higgins. Name this little sister of Beezus, the main character of a series of books by Beverly Cleary.

After initiation into the Khalsa in this religion, adherents must wear a wooden comb, known as the "kanga", and a steel bracelet, known as the "kara", which are two of the five K's. Arjun Dev compiled this religion's holy text, the Adi Granth, which contains many of the sayings of the first leader, or guru, of this religion. Identify this religion founded by Nanak, whose adherents are mostly found in the Punjab region.

This man chaired the 40 Committee that authorized the CIA backed coup of Salvador Allende in Chile. He negotiated with Zhou Enlai during Richard Nixon's 1972 visit to China. As National Security Advisor, he applied the term "détente" to relaxation of tensions with the Soviet Union. Name this Nobel Peace Prize winner and realpolitik advocate who served as Secretary of State at the end of the Vietnam War.

One book by this author features an adolescent girl with a Christian mother and a Jewish father who attempts a year-long independent study of people's beliefs while trying to deal with going through puberty. Another of her books features a five-year-old boy who names his myna bird Uncle Feather and constantly annoys his brother Peter. Name this author of Are You There God, It's Me, Margaret and Superfudge.

These objects have only three externally verifiable properties: mass, charge, and angular momentum, according to the no-hair theorem, and their size can be determined using the Schwarzschild radius. They can be formed following a supernova, and one of them is believed to be at the center of the Milky Way. Name these astronomical entities from which light cannot escape.

In 1983 this character was given a purple and green battle suit. This cancer survivor was fictionally the forty-third U.S. President. John Byrne rewrote this character as a white-collar criminal who runs a prominent aerospace company. He has been portrayed by Gene Hackman and Kevin Spacey in movies, and Michael Rosenbaum in Smallville. Name this bald supervillain known for his rivalry with Superman.

One story in this work tells of the rooster Chauntecleer outsmarting a fox. Another story is about three rogues killing each other under an oak tree in a quest to find Death. In another story, a knight is forced to find out what women most desire; that story is told by the Wife of Bath. Pilgrims on their way to visit an English cathedral city swap stories in what collection by Geoffrey Chaucer?

A "pillow" form of this substance forms underwater. "Domes" of this substance form from andesite. This substance can be classified, depending on the smoothness of its surface, as a'a or pahoehoe. It accumulates around a vent to form a cinder cone, and it solidifies to form igneous rock. For your answer give the term for magma that reaches the Earth's surface, often through a volcanic explosion.

The Isthmus of Tehuantepec is located in this nation, whose capital is overlooked by twin volcanoes called "Izta" and "Popo." States in this country include Michoacan, Veracruz, and the home of the Zapotec people, Oaxaca. Its capital, a city once called Tenochtitlan, was the center of the Aztec civilization. Name this Spanish-speaking nation located south of the Rio Grande River.
answers: United Mexican States; Estados Unidos Mexicanos

question: This book claims that the only two lamplighters who lead idle lives are at the North and South Poles, and it describes a King, a Geographer, and a Businessman. Much of it takes place after a crash landing in the Sahara, and its title character misses a flower growing on an asteroid. Name this work that begins with a picture of a snake eating an elephant that is often mistaken for a hat, a book by Antoine de Saint-Exupery.

One composer from this country depicted a "March to the Scaffold" in a five movement symphony, while another used a snare drum ostinato in a Spanish-inspired piece. A third composer from this country used a Mallarmé poem for his Prelude to the Afternoon of a Faun. Symphonie Fantastique, Bolero, and Clair de Lune were written in what country, home to Hector Berlioz, Maurice Ravel, and Claude Debussy?

This man was traded by the Reds for Edinson Volquez after his rookie season. In July 2011, Shannon Stone fell to his death while reaching for a ball that this player threw into the stands of Rangers Ballpark. The 2010 American League MVP was what left-handed hitting outfielder for the Texas Rangers who hit a go-ahead homer in the top of the 10th inning of game 6 in the 2011 World Series?

This nation's president declared a state of emergency after wildfires hit its western regions in July and August 2010. In June 2010, the United States arrested a SVR spy from this nation, Anna Chapman. In January 2011, this nation's Duma ratified a nuclear arms reduction treaty called New START. Name this nation led by Dmitry Medvedev from Moscow.

The antibiotic erythromycin works by disrupting this organelle, which contains E, P, and A sites on its large subunit. The parts of this organelle are assembled at nucleoli, and when bound to a membrane, these create the rough ER. Codons are translated at this organelle where the tRNA and mRNA meet. Name this organelle that is the site of protein synthesis

This modern-day country gained its independence with the Tydings-McDuffie Act. In World War II, the Battle of Bataan was fought over this land, and an American loss at that battle prompted Douglas MacArthur to say, "I Shall Return." It was once ruled by Ferdinand Marcos, whose wife Imelda was known for her collection of shoes. Name this country in which the Battle of Manila Bay took place.

This work begins with a word that means "what" and calls for attention. Its three battle scenes, including one against a dragon, are each followed by a funeral scene. While fighting without a weapon, the title character of this work tears an arm from an opponent in the dining hall Heorot, which was built by the Danish king Hrothgar. Name this Old English epic poem about a Geat (gate) warrior who defeats Grendel.

In one story by this author, General Lasalle's army saves the narrator from the Inquisition. Another narrator describes a sound like "a watch makes when enveloped in cotton." In a poem by this author, the title creature is perched on a "pallid bust of Pallas." Name this author of "The Pit and the Pendulum" and "The Tell-Tale Heart" who told of a bird crying "Nevermore" in "The Raven."

During this event, Attorney General Elliot Richardson and Deputy Attorney General William Ruckelshaus resigned in the Saturday Night Massacre. It attempted to cover up C.R.E.E.P.'s (CREEP's) attempt to bug the Democratic Party headquarters. It was uncovered by Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein with the help of Deep Throat. What scandal caused President Nixon to resign following his reelection?

The Darien Scheme was an attempt by Scotland to create another structure similar to this entity. The Hay-Bunau Varilla Treaty allowed the United States to begin constructing this entity. A zone around it was returned from the U.S. to its namesake country by a treaty signed by Jimmy Carter. Name this waterway that connects the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans through a Central American country.

This man sent the Great White Fleet on a tour of the world to impress Japan, and ended a conflict between Japan and Russia with the Treaty of Portsmouth. He recruited several college buddies to serve together as the Rough Riders unit during the Spanish-American War. He began "trustbusting" with the Standard Oil Case. Name this president from 1901 to 1909, whose nickname provided the name for a toy bear.

One folk hero from this nation killed policemen at Stringybark Creek; that man is "Ned" Kelly. One insurrection in this nation stripped William Bligh of his governorship; that insurrection is the Rum Rebellion. The "Stolen Generations" are children taken by the government of this nation from the Aborigines. Identify this nation where Arthur Phillip established a penal colony for the British Empire.

One conflict in this country saw the Duke of Guise fight for the throne with two other men named Henry. This country signed the Evian Accords in 1962 with Algeria. In the 8th century, this was the site where Charles Martel was victorious at the Battle of Tours. This country was led by Nicolas Sarkozy until the 2012 elections. Name this country once led by Charles de Gaulle.

This figure once tried to destroy mankind by tearing out an eye, which turned into Hathor. At night, he brings light to the darkness of the underworld. The disk above this deity's head is called Aton. Apep is depicted in an eternal struggle with this god, whose primary center of worship was at Heliopolis. In the form of Atum, he is the figure who gives light and warmth. Name this Egyptian sun deity.

Arias by this composer include Va, penseiro and La donna e mobile, This composer of an opera about the Duke of Mantua's court jester included a "Drinking Song" in an opera about Violetta Valéry, La Traviata. He also depicted Radames's dilemma in choosing between the titular Ethiopian slave girl and his loyalty to Egypt. Name this composer of Rigoletto and Aida.

One character on this show was a model who dated a girl named Marta before taking a job as a doorman. Another character on this show spent 3 days in law school and repeatedly sets things on fire. One of the main character's friends is a tech wizard with an overbearing mother, while the other is a meat-addicted delinquent who co-hosts the title show. Name this Nickelodeon sitcom starring Miranda Cosgrove as the host of an internet webcast.

One novel by this writer is about a man who enters an extinct volcano in Iceland and emerges in Italy. In another novel by him, a detective named Fix is suspicious of the protagonist, Phileas Fogg. In another work, Pierre Arronax narrates on the Nautilus about Captain Nemo. Name this author of A Journey to the Center of the Earth, Around the World in Eighty Days, and Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea.

One law named for this scientist is due to the conservation of angular momentum, and states that a line drawn from a planet to the center of its orbit will sweep out equal areas in equal times. This writer of Astronomia nova and Mysterium cosmographicum analyzed data collected by Tycho Brahe [TEE-koh BRAH] to develop that statement as well as to determine that planets' orbits are ellipses. Name this German astronomer who published three laws of planetary motion.

The size of these objects is given by the Schwarzschild ("SHWARTZ child") radius. According to quantum mechanics, these objects emit Hawking radiation. One of them, Sagittarius A Star, sits at the center of our galaxy and has four million times the mass of our sun. What are these objects in outer space from which supposedly nothing, not even light, can escape?

This poem's original form notes that the speaker and his addressee have "rin about the braes" and "paidl't i' the burn."
